9 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
10 That Section(s) 21–259.3 of Article – Health – General of the Annotated Code of Maryland
11 be renumbered to be Section(s) 21–259.4.
12 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
13 as follows:
14 Article – Commercial Law
15 13–301.
16 Unfair, abusive, or deceptive trade practices include any:
17 (14) Violation of a provision of:
18 (xlvii) Title 14, Subtitle 50 of this article; [or]
19 (xlviii) Section 13–411.1(c)(2) of the Transportation Article; or
20 (XLIX) SECTION 21–259.2 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL
21 ARTICLE; OR
22 Article – Health – General
23 21–101.
24 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
25 (e) (1) “Cosmetic” means any substance, or any component of a substance, that
26 is intended to be rubbed, poured, sprinkled, or sprayed on, introduced into, or otherwise
27 applied to the human body for cleansing, beautifying, promoting attractiveness, or altering
28 appearance.
29 (2) “Cosmetic” does not include soap.
30 21–259.2.

4 HOUSE BILL 1533
1 (a) In this section:
2 (1) “Ingredient” means any single chemical entity or mixture used as a
3 component in the manufacture of a cosmetic product; and
4 (2) “Ingredient” does not include an incidental ingredient, as described in
5 21 C.F.R. § 701.3(l).
6 (b) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, a person may not
7 knowingly manufacture, sell, deliver, hold, or offer for sale in the State a cosmetic product
8 that contains any of the following intentionally added ingredients:
9 (1) Dibutyl phthalate (CAS no. 84–74–2);
10 (2) Diethylhexyl phthalate (CAS no. 117–81–7);
11 (3) Formaldehyde (CAS no. 50–00–0);
12 (4) Paraformaldehyde (CAS no. 30525–89–4);
13 (5) Methylene glycol (CAS no. 463–57–0);
14 (6) Quaternium–15 (CAS no. 51229–78–8);
15 (7) Mercury (CAS no. 7439–97–6);
16 (8) Isobutylparaben (CAS no. 4247–02–3);
17 (9) Isopropylparaben (CAS no. 4191–73–5);
18 (10) m–Phenylenediamine and its salts (CAS no. 108–45–2);
19 (11) o–Phenylenediamine and its salts (CAS no. 95–54–5); or
20 (12) LEAD (CAS NO. 7439–92–1); OR
21 (13) The following per– and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) and their
22 salts:
23 (i) Perfluorooctane sulfonate (PFOS) or
24 heptadecafluorooctane–1–sulfonic acid (CAS no. 1763–23–1);
25 (ii) Potassium perfluorooctanesulfonate or potassium
26 heptadecafluorooctane–1–sulfonate (CAS no. 2795–39–3);
27 (iii) Diethanolamine perfluorooctane sulfonate (CAS no.
28 70225–14–8);

HOUSE BILL 1533 5
1 (iv) Ammonium perfluorooctane sulfonate or ammonium
2 heptadecafluorooctanesulfonate (CAS no. 29081–56–9);
3 (v) Lithium perfluorooctane sulfonate or lithium
4 heptadecafluorooctanesulfonate (CAS no. 29457–72–5);
5 (vi) Perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA) (CAS no. 335–67–1);
6 (vii) Ammonium pentadecafluorooctanoate (CAS no. 3825–26–1);
7 (viii) Nonadecafluorodecanoic acid (CAS no. 335–76–2);
8 (ix) Ammonium nonadecafluorodecanoate (CAS no. 3108–42–7);
9 (x) Sodium nonadecafluorodecanoate (CAS no. 3830–45–3);
10 (xi) Perfluorononanoic acid (PFNA) (CAS no. 375–95–1);
11 (xii) Sodium heptadecafluorononanoate (CAS no. 21049–39–8); or
12 (xiii) Ammonium perfluorononanoate (CAS no. 4149–60–4).
13 (c) A person is not in violation of this section if the person manufactures, sells,
14 delivers, holds, or offers for sale in the State a cosmetic product that:
15 (1) Was manufactured through a process intended to comply with this
16 section; and
17 (2) Contains a technically unavoidable trace quantity of an ingredient
18 listed in subsection (b) of this section due to:
19 (i) An impurity of a natural or synthetic ingredient;
20 (ii) The manufacturing process;
21 (iii) Storage; or
22 (iv) Packaging.
23 (D) (1) IN ADDITION TO ANY OTHER PENALTIES UNDER THIS TITLE, A
24 PERSON WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION IS LIABLE FOR CIVIL DAMAGES RESULTING
25 FROM ACTUAL HARM SUSTAINED BY THE INDIVIDUAL RESULTING FROM THE
26 VIOLATION.

6 HOUSE BILL 1533
1 (2) AN ACTION UNDER THIS SECTION MUST BE BROUGHT WITHIN 3
2 YEARS AFTER THE DATE ON WHICH THE PLAINTIFF DISCOVERED OR REASONABLY
3 SHOULD HAVE DISCOVERED THAT THE EXPOSURE TO AN INGREDIENT IN VIOLATION
4 OF THIS SECTION WAS THE PROXIMATE CAUSE OF THE INJURY SUSTAINED BY THE
5 PLAINTIFF.
6 (3) IN ANY ACTION BROUGHT TO ENFORCE THIS SECTION, A COURT
7 MAY AWARD REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES TO A PREVAILING PLAINTIFF:
8 (I) TREBLE DAMAGES;
9 (II) IF THE VIOLATION WAS WILLFUL, PUNITIVE DAMAGES; AND
10 (III) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES.
11 (E) (1) THE DEPARTMENT MAY INVESTIGATE ANY COMPLAINT ALLEGING
12 THAT A PERSON HAS VIOLATED THIS SECTION.
13 (2) ON RECEIPT OF A COMPLAINT, A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE
14 DEPARTMENT, AT A REASONABLE TIME, MAY ENTER AND INSPECT THE PREMISES OF
15 THE PERSON LOCATED IN THE STATE TO DETERMINE COMPLIANCE WITH THIS
16 SECTION.
17 (3) THE PERSON MAY NOT:
18 (I) REFUSE TO GRANT ACCESS TO A REPRESENTATIVE WHO
19 REQUESTS TO ENTER AND INSPECT THE PREMISES OF THE PERSON UNDER
20 PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION; OR
21 (II) INTERFERE WITH AN INSPECTION UNDER PARAGRAPH (2)
22 OF THIS SUBSECTION.
23 (4) AN INVESTIGATION OF A PREMISES OF A PERSON CONDUCTED
24 UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MAY INCLUDE SAMPLING OF A COSMETIC PRODUCT TO
25 DETERMINE IF THE COSMETIC PRODUCT CONTAINS A TECHNICALLY UNAVOIDABLE
26 TRACE QUANTITY OF AN INGREDIENT LISTED IN SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION.
27 21–259.3.
28 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “FUND” MEANS THE HARMFUL HAIR CHEMICAL
29 RESTITUTION FUND.
30 (B) THERE IS A HARMFUL HAIR CHEMICAL RESTITUTION FUND.

HOUSE BILL 1533 7
1 (C) THE PURPOSE OF THE FUND IS TO SUPPORT THE RESEARCH AND
2 TREATMENT, INCLUDING SCREENINGS AND DIAGNOSIS, OF FIBROIDS, UTERINE
3 CANCER, HAIR LOSS, AND RELATED CONDITIONS CAUSED BY HARMFUL HAIR
4 CHEMICALS.
5 (D) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADMINISTER THE FUND.
6 (E) (1) THE FUND IS A SPECIAL, NONLAPSING FUND THAT IS NOT
7 SUBJECT TO § 7–302 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE.
8 (2) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL HOLD THE FUND SEPARATELY,
9 AND THE COMPTROLLER SHALL ACCOUNT FOR THE FUND.
10 (F) THE FUND CONSISTS OF:
11 (1) ALL FUNDS, EXCLUDING FUNDS RECEIVED BY THE AGGRIEVED
12 PARTY AND THE COSTS OF THE ACTION THE ATTORNEY GENERAL IS ENTITLED TO
13 RECOVER, RECEIVED BY THE DIVISION OF CONSUMER PROTECTION IN THE OFFICE
14 OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL FROM ENFORCING § 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE
15 UNDER THE CONSUMER PROTECTION ACT; AND
16 (2) INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND.
17 (G) (1) THE FUND SHALL BE USED FOR:
18 (I) PROVIDING GRANTS FOR THE SUPPORT OF THE RESEARCH
19 AND TREATMENT, INCLUDING SCREENINGS AND DIAGNOSIS, OF FIBROIDS, UTERINE
20 CANCER, HAIR LOSS, AND RELATED CONDITIONS CAUSED BY HARMFUL HAIR
21 CHEMICALS;
22 (II) CARRYING OUT ANY LAWS ENACTED TO BENEFIT VICTIMS
23 OF A VIOLATION OF § 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
24 (III) PROVIDING RESTITUTION TO VICTIMS OF A VIOLATION OF §
25 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
26 (2) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
27 ADOPT REGULATIONS TO ADMINISTER THE FUND.
28 (H) (1) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL INVEST THE MONEY OF THE FUND
29 IN THE SAME MANNER AS OTHER STATE MONEY MAY BE INVESTED.
30 (2) ANY INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND SHALL BE CREDITED TO
31 THE FUND.

8 HOUSE BILL 1533
1 (I) EXPENDITURES FROM THE FUND MAY BE MADE ONLY IN ACCORDANCE
2 WITH THE STATE BUDGET.
3 (J) MONEY EXPENDED FROM THE FUND FOR THE SUPPORT OF RESEARCH
4 AND TREATMENT UNDER SUBSECTION (G) OF THIS SECTION IS SUPPLEMENTAL TO
5 AND IS NOT INTENDED TO TAKE THE PLACE OF FUNDING THAT OTHERWISE WOULD
6 BE APPROPRIATED FOR THE SUPPORT OF RESEARCH AND TREATMENT.
7 Article – State Finance and Procurement
8 6–226.
9 (a) (2) (i) This paragraph does not apply in fiscal years 2024 through 2028.
10 (ii) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, and unless
11 inconsistent with a federal law, grant agreement, or other federal requirement or with the
12 terms of a gift or settlement agreement, net interest on all State money allocated by the
13 State Treasurer under this section to special funds or accounts, and otherwise entitled to
14 receive interest earnings, as accounted for by the Comptroller, shall accrue to the General
15 Fund of the State.
16 (iii) The provisions of subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph do not
17 apply to the following funds:
18 212. the Department of Social and Economic Mobility Special
19 Fund; [and]
20 213. the Population Health Improvement Fund; AND
21 214. THE HARMFUL HAIR CHEMICALS RESTITUTION
22 FUND.
23 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
24 July 1, 2026.
